  CORE ARGUMENT: Wright argues that feminist critics of Habermas (particularly those emphasizing the ethics of care) misread his discourse theory as excluding particularity. He shows that Habermasian discourse ethics contains resources for accommodating perspective-taking and particularity, specifically through the requirement that discourse participants take the perspective of those affected by norms under discussion. The feminist critique applies to Kant but not necessarily to the dialogical version in Habermas.

  RELEVANCE: Represents a philosophically careful defense of Habermasian discourse ethics against the feminist charge that it systematically excludes the concrete other and embodied experience. Wright shows that some feminist critiques conflate Kant and Habermas, providing a resource for distinguishing which critiques of Habermas are well-targeted from which are not.

  POSITION: Sympathetic defense of Habermas against feminist critique, arguing that dialogue transforms Kantian impartiality in ways that accommodate particularity.
  },
  keywords = {wright, feminist-defense, discourse-ethics, particularity, perspective-taking, Medium}
}

@article{delanty1997habermas,
  author = {Delanty, Gerard},
  title = {{Habermas} and Occidental Rationalism: The Politics of Identity, Social Learning, and the Cultural Limits of Moral Universalism},
  journal = {Sociological Theory},
  year = {1997},
  volume = {15},
  number = {1},
  pages = {30--59},
  doi = {10.1111/0735-2751.00022},
  abstract = {While Habermas's theory of communicative action is deeply critical of all kinds of ethnocentrism, proposing a discursive concept of universal morality which transcends culture, a residual Eurocentrism still pervades it. Habermas's theory rests on a notion of modernity which is tied to Occidental rationalism, and when viewed in the global context or in the context of deeply divided societies it is problematic. The theory fails to grasp that universal morality can be articulated in more than one cultural form and in more than one logic of development. However, his theory can be defended against its Eurocentric bias if it shifts its emphasis from a de-contexualized and transcendental critique of communication rooted in Occidental rationalism to a cosmopolitan model of contemporary cultural transformation. Crucial to that task is a weaker notion of rationality which recognizes that the problem of universality is also a cognitive cultural problem and not just a normative one. Bringing culture and identity to the foreground will involve making room for a level of discourse focused less on consensual agreement than on cultural understanding.},
  abstract_source = {openalex},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Delanty argues that Habermas's communicative rationality, despite its universalist claims, remains embedded in an Occidental framework of social learning that privileges Western patterns of modernization. He develops the tension between Habermas's formal universalism (procedural requirements of discourse) and his substantive Eurocentrism (the assumption that Western modernity embodies a higher stage of social rationality), arguing that the cultural limits of Habermasian universalism become visible in cross-cultural contexts.

  RELEVANCE: Provides sociological analysis of why Habermas's universalism has cultural limits that go beyond mere procedural formalism -- directly relevant to assessing Dussel's charge that communicative rationality is structurally Eurocentric even at the level of formal claims, not just in its empirical application.

  POSITION: Critical assessment of the cultural limits of Habermasian universalism from a sociology-of-knowledge perspective.
  },
  keywords = {delanty, eurocentrism, universalism, habermas, occidental-rationalism, Medium}
}

